knowledge_graph.title: Gin
knowledge_graph.description: Gin is a distilled alcoholic drink flavoured with juniper berries and other botanical ingredients. Gin originated as a medicinal liquor made by monks and alchemists across Europe.

related_questions.question: What kind of alcohol is gin?
related_questions.snippet: Gin is a spirit typically made from a base of grain, such as wheat or barley, which is first fermented and then distilled. To be classified as gin, however, the predominant flavor must be of juniper berries, otherwise the drink cannot be called gin, by law. Most gins have anywhere from 35% to 55% ABV.

related_questions.question: Is gin stronger than vodka?
related_questions.snippet: Both vodka and gin have a similar ABV of 40%, although outside the US, especially in eastern European countries, vodka ABV can exceed 80%.

related_questions.question: What is gin basically?
related_questions.snippet: Gin is a colorless spirit obtained by distilling an aqueous mixture of alcohol together with aromatic plant materials, generally juniper berries (Juniperus communis L.), to which water and alcohol and at times fruit juices, extracts, and/or essential oils of fruits may be added.
